										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_451342534_Fotor-16x9-1024x576.jpg" alt="a senior couple, an elderly man and woman in park listening to music with earbuds or headphones" class="wp-image-222590" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_451342534_Fotor-16x9-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_451342534_Fotor-16x9-300x169.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2018/11/shutterstock_451342534_Fotor-16x9-768x432.jpg 768w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>Rochester, Minn. — People around the globe are living longer — but not necessarily healthier — lives, according to Mayo Clinic research. A study of <a href="https://www.who.int/countries" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">183 World Health Organization (WHO) member countries</a> found those additional years of life are increasingly fraught with disease. This research by <a href="https://www.mayo.edu/research/faculty/terzic-andre-m-d-ph-d/bio-00084640" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Andre Terzic, M.D., Ph.D.</a>, and Armin Garmany documents a widening gap between lifespan and healthspan. Their paper is published in <a href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamanetworkopen/fullarticle/10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2024.50241?utm_source=For_The_Media&amp;amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;amp;utm_campaign=ftm_links&amp;amp;utm_term=121124" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">JAMA Network Open</a>.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Global-Healthspan-Lifespan-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v2-02-1024x576.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-397657" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Global-Healthspan-Lifespan-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v2-02-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Global-Healthspan-Lifespan-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v2-02-300x169.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Global-Healthspan-Lifespan-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v2-02-768x432.jpg 768w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Global-Healthspan-Lifespan-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v2-02-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Global-Healthspan-Lifespan-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v2-02-2048x1152.jpg 2048w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="alignright size-medium is-resized"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="300" height="200" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/11/Terzic3-300x200.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-397273" style="width:236px;height:auto" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/11/Terzic3-300x200.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/11/Terzic3-768x512.jpg 768w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/11/Terzic3.jpg 800w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Andre Terzic, M.D., Ph.D.</figcaption></figure></div>


<p>"The data show that gains in longevity are not matched with equivalent advances in healthy longevity. Growing older often means more years of life burdened with disease," says Dr. Terzic, senior author. "This research has important practice and policy implications by bringing attention to a growing threat to the quality of longevity and the need to close the healthspan-lifespan gap."</p>



<p>Dr. Terzic is the Marriott Family Director, Comprehensive Cardiac Regenerative Medicine for the <a href="https://www.mayo.edu/research/centers-programs/center-regenerative-biotherapeutics/about" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Mayo Clinic Center for Regenerative Biotherapeutics</a> and Marriott Family Professor of Cardiovascular Research at Mayo Clinic.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Lifespan-healthspan gap largest in the U.S.</h2>



<p>Life expectancy, or lifespan, increased from 79.2 to 80.7 years in women and from 74.1 to 76.3 years in men between 2000 and 2019, according to WHO estimates. Healthspan describes the number of years a person has lived a healthy, active, disease-free life. However, the number of years those people were living in good health did not correspondingly increase. The average global gap in lifespan versus healthspan was 9.6 years in 2019, the last year of available statistics. That represents a 13% increase since 2000.</p>



<p>The U.S. recorded the world's highest average lifespan-health span divide, with Americans living 12.4 years on average with disability and sickness. This increase from 10.9 years in 2000 comes as the U.S. also reported the highest burden of chronic disease. Mental health, substance use disorders and musculoskeletal conditions were the key contributors to illness nationally.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Healthspan-Lifespan-across-WHO-member-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v3-1024x576.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-397658" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Healthspan-Lifespan-across-WHO-member-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v3-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Healthspan-Lifespan-across-WHO-member-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v3-300x169.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Healthspan-Lifespan-across-WHO-member-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v3-768x432.jpg 768w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Healthspan-Lifespan-across-WHO-member-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v3-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/12/Healthspan-Lifespan-across-WHO-member-Gap-Graphic-16-9-v3-2048x1152.jpg 2048w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>



<p>In addition, the study found a 25% gender disparity worldwide. Across 183 surveyed countries, women experienced a 2.4-year larger gap in lifespan versus healthspan than men. Neurological, musculoskeletal, urinary and genital tract disorders contributed to extended years of poor health among women.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="alignright size-medium is-resized"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="300" height="200" src="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/11/Garmany-WF3411203_0043-300x200.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-397271" style="width:244px;height:auto" srcset="https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/11/Garmany-WF3411203_0043-300x200.jpg 300w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/11/Garmany-WF3411203_0043-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/11/Garmany-WF3411203_0043-768x512.jpg 768w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/11/Garmany-WF3411203_0043-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/n7-mcnn/7bcc9724adf7b803/uploads/2024/11/Garmany-WF3411203_0043-2048x1365.jpg 2048w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Armin Garmany</figcaption></figure></div>


<p>"The widening healthspan-lifespan gap globally points to the need for an accelerated pivot to proactive wellness-centric care systems," says Armin Garmany, first author and an M.D./Ph.D. student in Mayo Clinic <a href="https://college.mayo.edu/academics/mayo-clinic-alix-school-of-medicine/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Alix School of Medicine</a> and Mayo Clinic <a href="https://college.mayo.edu/academics/biomedical-research-training/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Graduate School of Biomedical Sciences</a>. "Identifying contributors to the gap unique to each geography can help inform healthcare interventions specific to each country and region."</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Healthspan research</h2>



<p>The Mayo Clinic research team studied statistics from the <a href="https://www.who.int/data/gho" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">WHO Global Health Observatory</a>. This cross-sectional study provided data on life expectancy, health-adjusted life expectancy, years lived with disease and years of life lost among member states. The healthspan-lifespan gap for each member state was calculated by subtracting health-adjusted life expectancy from life expectancy.</p>



<p>The research team recommends additional exploration of demographic, health and economic characteristics to better define the disease patterns that are shaping the lifespan-healthspan disparities. Funding for the paper was provided by the <a href="https://www.jwasmarriottfoundation.org/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Marriott Family Foundation</a>, <a href="https://www.nih.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">National Institutes of Health</a> and <a href="https://www.nigms.nih.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">National Institute of General Medical Sciences</a>.</p>



